metadata.name: Loom #5
metadata.description:
Loom is an exploration on texture, points, lines and noise on color in a gridsystem. 

You can self-curate your token, by clicking the canvas colors change in the cells, with the g key you can toggle between local change (cell) or global change (all cells), with the c key you can remove a color, with the v key you can reset colors, with the x key you can download a higher resolution version.


Press 's' to save a png image
Press 'j' to save a jpg image
Press 'x' to save a higher resolution png
Press 'c' to remove a color
Press 'v' to reset colors

metadata.name: Departure Within Shattered Windmills #95
metadata.description:
I wrote the following when reviewing the outputs...

The wind is gone,
My windmill falls,
I reach out to catch the pieces.
Half fall in my right hand,
The others in my left,
Two stacks of colored paper.
I’m holding my windmill,
I feel the breeze in my hair.
Each hand is empty,
My windmill rises,
I can see the wind.

'Departure Within Shattered Windmills' was originally inspired by suprematism, and then started to gain more complexity. It is still a combination of simple features, subdivided quads drawn on different planes of perspective. Chaos simulated by many organized grids. Countless pieces of a windmill.

25% of the royalties for each edition will pass to the original minter.

Each output is generated from code written in p5js.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

metadata.name: Pillars of Tomorrow #60
metadata.description:
Our vision is to create meaningful generative artworks that express human sentiments about their social experiences.

We’re currently focused on experiences centered around celebration, and we’ve chosen a theme that connects people through music.
Music has the power to evoke a wide range of emotions within us, especially when experienced through a collective experience.

We wanted to generate an artistic script that visually captures these expressions. 

Our first music NFT collection reflects human sentiments towards Tomorrowland 2022. 
It's a creative collaboration with dahleea, an artist dedicated to colors, who gave us the inspiration for the visuals you are seeing through one of her beautiful and colorful artworks.

Coding, music, and art collide to recreate emotions expressed by people coming together from all over the world to share music and connection at one of the world’s leading music festivals. 

The creative process:

Data was collected via emotion analysis using Twitter’s API. Our data is derived from emotion analysis models to extract the emotion scores (Happiness, Anger, Sadness, Fear, and Surprise) from 105,762 tweets, written in English, and containing mention of ‘Tomorrowland' between July 15, 2022, to August 8, 2022. 

Our analysis demonstrated the following emotions:

Happiness: 38%
Anger 8%
Sadness: 26%
Fear: 28%

Music:

In Pillars of Tomorrow, there are 4 instruments: bass, piano, percussion (hi-hat, kick, snare, claps, fx sounds), and a quiet pad. All the rhythms are self-written using Ableton, exported, and randomly selected to create the backbone of our generative music NFT.

This music piece has 4 different parts (basic, drop, break, after-drop) which are looped 3 times. All parts include different rhythm variations which are chosen randomly. 

The generative harmony is present in the basic and after-drop parts. The key to generating harmony is using the emotion percentages above as possibilities for the next piano chord and melody to sound happy or sad.  
We chose to distort our bass sound according to anger trait values, as distortion can turn a mild bass into an aggressive one. 

Finally, there is also an emotion of surprise, which is associated with a special background and the sound of bells ringing.  The surprise element trait of the mints will be revealed after the Pillars of Tomorrow collection is fully minted.

We wanted to make a dynamic collection that would give you the feeling of a live music event, an interactive experience. A big stage flowing with music and diverse human expressions.

Arrow Up (View pillars from above)
Arrow down (go to starting position)
Arrow left/right (camera moving direction)

AWSD work as arrows as well

For an optimal experience, we recommend using Google Chrome.

#CodingIsArt

metadata.name: Pseudopodia #49
metadata.description:
Pseudopods are small temporary growths used by micro-organisms for moving about or ingesting food. Here is an artistic depiction of many pseudopods as viewed under the microscope.

Be patient, there are 3 rather slow drawing passes, followed by a final quick pass. The drawing passes give the piece a 3-dimensional aspect.

Press "s" to save image as a .png file.

metadata.name: Bleached #94
metadata.description:
Bleached is a work inspired by mid-20th century art. I have always been impressed by its beauty and charm of non-ideality. How art gave birth to order out of utter chaos.
Inspired, I transferred the spirit of its freedom and expression into my algorithm.

metadata.name: Chroma #44
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

'Chroma' attempts to balance a large color palette.

Each output consists of various geometric designs, displayed orthographically in rows, hopefully producing a pleasing result :) 

In live mode:
Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x2000px PNG.

metadata.name: Unicorn #6
metadata.description:
The unicorn is a legendary creature that has been described since antiquity as a beast with a single large, pointed, spiraling horn projecting from its forehead.

In European literature and art, the unicorn has for the last thousand years or so been depicted as a white horse-like or goat-like animal with a long straight horn with spiralling grooves, cloven hooves, and sometimes a goat's beard. In the Middle Ages and Renaissance, it was commonly described as an extremely wild woodland creature, a symbol of purity and grace, which could be captured only by a virgin. In encyclopedias, its horn was described as having the power to render poisoned water potable and to heal sickness. In medieval and Renaissance times, the tusk of the narwhal was sometimes sold as a unicorn horn.  Wikipedia
